  "text": "The Rust borrow checker's MIR analysis chain traces through the following key components:\n\n## Entry Point\nThe `mir_borrowck` function in compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/lib.rs (line 117) is the query provider that serves as the main entry point for borrow checking. It initializes a `BorrowCheckRootCtxt` and calls `do_mir_borrowck()` to orchestrate the entire checking process.\n\n## Borrow Set Collection\nThe `BorrowSet` struct in compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/borrow_set.rs (line 16) is the fundamental data structure that collects all borrows in the MIR. It uses the `GatherBorrows` visitor (line 222) to traverse the MIR and identify all borrow statements, building a location_map that maps each borrow location to a `BorrowData` structure. The `BorrowSet::build` method (line 169) constructs this set by visiting all basic blocks in preorder, collecting borrow reservations and two-phase activation points.\n\n## Live Range Computation (NLL)\nThe `RegionInferenceContext` in compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/region_infer/mod.rs (line 79) performs the Non-Lexical Lifetimes (NLL) analysis to compute live ranges for borrows. It manages `LivenessValues` (from compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/region_infer/values.rs) which track which region variables are live at each program point. The live range computation determines the actual lifetime of each borrow based on control flow and usage patterns.\n\n## Place Conflict Detection\nThe place conflict detection is implemented through two functions in compiler/rustc_borrowck/src/places_conflict.rs:\n- `places_conflict` (line 81): A public helper function for checking if places conflict with a mutable borrow and deep access.\n- `borrow_conflicts_with_place` (line 104): The core function that determines whether a borrow place conflicts with an access place by walking projections in lockstep, checking for overlaps based on the borrow kind and access depth.\n\nThe conflict detection uses a sophisticated algorithm that walks the \"root\" of the